    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix stack buffer overflow in nas_proc_get_loc_info\n\n### Summary\nThe function `nas_proc_get_loc_info()` in `nas_proc.c` was using unsafe `sprintf` calls that could cause stack buffer overflow when formatting TAC and CI values. This has been fixed by replacing with bounds-checked `snprintf` calls.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/nas_proc.c`: \n  - Replaced unsafe `sprintf` calls with `snprintf` in `nas_proc_get_loc_info()`\n  - Updated include comment to reflect use of `snprintf`\n  - Function now properly limits output to prevent buffer overflow when formatting TAC (4 hex chars) and CI (8 hex chars) values\n\n### Reproduction\nThe issue could be triggered when the NAS procedure manager calls `nas_proc_get_loc_info()` to retrieve location information. With certain network configurations or malformed TAC/CI values, the `sprintf` calls could write beyond the allocated buffer boundaries, potentially causing:\n- Segmentation fault due to stack corruption\n- Unpredictable behavior or crashes\n- Security vulnerabilities from controlled stack memory overwrite\n\nThe fix ensures that exactly 5 bytes are written for TAC (4 hex chars + null terminator) and 9 bytes for CI (8 hex chars + null terminator), matching the buffer sizes allocated in the calling code.\n"
}